			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Too much aggro...<a name="69569"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Nov 12 04 8:14 AM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span>Using the above weaps, you are producing raw damage as fast as your tank is building hate.  Yah, you'll steal aggro for a round or two, until he pounds taunt again.  But honestly, pounding /fade mid fight will drop all aggro back on the tank, and nothing in the world will let you get it back.
<br />

<br />
Hate/Aggro accumilation is like a race.  Bards get a little head start from HoS/Slow on pull, but the second that first arrow hits, its back to the tank.  Then its his weaps vs yours.  if you do 100 dps, and he is doing the same, its your DD procs vs his Aggro procs and how often he pounds /taunt, /bash, etc.  But if his base DPS is higher than yours, good luck.
<br />

<br />
To prove it, grab any random mob and tank it to 50% or less, then let your War friend /taunt.  Its amazing how fast that mob will forget you.  If you, as a bard are getting consistent aggro from anything other than low hp aggro, and rampages, your tank is being lazy and relying on his own melee and procs to hold aggro.  That's about the same as a bard singing one song while he melees, IMO.
<br />

<br />
The effective use of /taunt will completely remove your ability to grab aggro.
<br />

<br />
The amount of aggro our songs produce is minimal.  Any hate we get is from direct damage (excluding prox aggro and assist aggro, if we aren't the puller).  We are near the bottom when it comes to raw dps, and without anything that gives us raw hate, we will always remain there.
<br />

<br />
Rappa</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
